WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.360
Get ready because this RStudio shortcut tip will save you so much time.

00:00:03.360 --> 00:00:07.920
Do you ever find yourself re-running the same chunk of code over and over again,

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:12.480
slightly modifying it each time? Say some data manipulation task where you're building a plot

00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:17.440
in which you're iterating as you slowly build it up. For years I'd run my chunk, edit it,

00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:21.120
and then use my mouse to re-select that code chunk to run it again.

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:25.680
You don't need to touch that mouse. Or trackpad. Or little red ball thingy.

00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:29.520
Here's a quick example. I select this range of code, run it, creating this plot.

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:32.720
Then I realized I wanted to make a bunch of changes. Refining the plot,

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:36.799
adding labels, fixing bugs. As I'm iterating and I want to check how these changes look

00:00:36.799 --> 00:00:39.279
in the new plot, all I have to do is run my new shortcut.

00:00:39.279 --> 00:00:42.560
This shortcut will run the same region of code over again,

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:47.439
even if you've edited it or expanded it. And what do we mean by region exactly?

00:00:47.439 --> 00:00:51.279
Even if you add new lines of code, the shortcut will automatically pick those up.

00:00:51.279 --> 00:00:55.439
And that's Command Option P on a Mac or Control Option P on Windows.

00:00:55.439 --> 00:00:58.639
And follow for more Posit Tips like this.

